notesStmt.note: This is an illustrated and illuminated Safavid copy of the Khamsah (quintet) of Amīr Khusraw Dihlavī (d. 725 AH / 1325 CE), written by Pīr Ḥusayn al-Kātib al-Shīrāzī in 935 AH / 1529 CE. The codex opens with a double-page illuminated frontispiece with verses in honor of the poet Mir (Amir) Khusraw (fols. 1b-2a). There are four illuminated incipit pages introducing the individual poems, and thirteen paintings illustrate the text. The lacquer binding, which is not original to the manuscript, has a hunting scene on the upper and lower boards. The lower board is inscribed yā Shāh Najaf (oh, King of Najaf, i.e. ʿAlī) and is dated 1271 AH / 1854 CE.

msContents.textLang: The primary language in this manuscript is Persian. The secondary language of this manuscript is Arabic.

msItem.title: Khamsah-i Dihlavī
خمسه دهلوى
msItem.incipit: بسم الله الرحمن الرحيم خطبه قدست بملك قديم...
msItem.note: Contains the five poems: Maṭlaʿ al-anvār (fols. 1b-55a), Shīrīn va Khusraw (fols. 55b-114a), Majnūn va Laylá (fols. 114b-155a), Āyinah-i Iskandarī (fols. 155b-224a), Hasht bihisht (fols. 224b-274a); some folios damaged, causing loss of text

colophon.note: tamma al-kitāb bi-ʿawn Allāh al-Malik al-Wahhāb wa-ḥusn tawfīqih fī yawm al-arbaʿāʾ /1/ thālith ʿishrīn [sic] shahr Dhī al-Qaʿdah sanat khams wa-thalāthīn wa- /2/ tisʿimi<ʾ>ah min al-hijrah al-nabawīyah al-muṣṭafawīyah ṣlʿm (=ṣallá Allāh ʿalayhi wa-sallama) /3/

layoutDesc.layout: Framing lines in blue, black, and gold; text written horizontally and obliquely

handDesc.handNote: Written in nastaʿlīq script in black with sections/headings in gold and blue

decoDesc.decoNote: Thirteen illustrations (fols. 23a, 34b, 39a, 66a, 123a, 130b, 173b, 186b, 207b, 232b, 244b, 254b, and 267b); double-page illuminated frontispiece (fols. 1b-2a); illuminated incipit pages with titlepieces (Shīrīn va Khusraw [fol. 55b], Majnūn va Laylá [fol. 114b], Āyinah-i Iskandarī [fol. 155b], and Hasht bihisht [fol. 224b]); framing lines in blue, black, and gold

decoNote.title: Binding
decoNote.note: This lacquer binding depicts a hunting scene and dates to the thirteenth century AH / nineteenth CE.

decoNote.title: Double-page illuminated frontispiece
decoNote.note: This is the right side of a double-page illuminated frontispiece introducing the first poem of the Khamsah, Maṭlaʿ al-anvār. The inscription consists of verses in honor of Mīr (Amīr) Khusraw.

decoNote.title: Double-page illuminated frontispiece
decoNote.note: This is the left side of a double-page illuminated frontispiece introducing the first poem of the Khamsah, Maṭlaʿ al-anvār. The inscription consists of verses in honor of Mīr (Amīr) Khusraw.

decoNote.title: The prophet Khizr paying a visit to a pious man
Four men die of thirst in a desert
decoNote.note: Four men die of thirst in a desert, each refusing the water offered by a stranger on a camel until his companion has drunk.

decoNote.title: A king out hunting accidentally kills a young man
decoNote.note: A king out hunting accidentally kills a young man and offers to compensate his mother with his own life or a platter of gold.

decoNote.title: Illuminated incipit page with titlepiece
decoNote.note: This illuminated incipit page has a titlepiece inscribed with the title of the second poem of the Khamsah, Kitāb-i Shīrīn va Khusraw, in white ink on a gold ground.

decoNote.title: Khusraw meets Shīrīn while hunting
Incipit page with illuminated titlepiece
decoNote.note: This illuminated incipit page has a titlepiece inscribed with the title of the third poem of the Khamsah, Kitāb-i Majnūn Laylī, in white ink on a gold ground.

decoNote.title: Laylá and Majnūn fall in love at school
Nawfal battles Laylá’s clan on behalf of Majnūn
Incipit page with illuminated titlepiece
decoNote.note: This illuminated incipit page has a titlepiece inscribed with the title of the fourth poem of the Khamsah, Kitāb-i āyinah-i Iskandarī, in white ink on a gold ground.

decoNote.title: Alexander the Great lassos a Chinese warrior
Alexander the Great entertains Kanīfū
Alexander the Great confers with wise men
decoNote.note: Iskandar (Alexander the Great) confers with wise men about his intention to investigate the mysteries of the deep.

decoNote.title: Incipit page with illuminated titlepiece
decoNote.note: This illuminated incipit page has a titlepiece inscribed with the title of the fifth poem of the Khamsah, Kitāb-i hasht bihisht, in white ink on a gold ground.

decoNote.title: Bahrām Gūr displays his hunting skills before Dilārām
Bahrām Gūr in the green pavilion
Bahrām Gūr in the blue pavilion
Bahrām Gūr in the white pavilion

binding.p: Lacquer boards (without flap) depicting hunting scenes with a gazelle and a bear; inscription on the lower board, dated 1271 AH / 1854 CE, reads: yā Shāh Najaf (oh, King of Najaf, i.e. ʿAlī)
